{"author":{"id":"d090680751e9d81548e628ee372337dbb14df0993593a8afe125eaa85e30d5d8"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1687295858,"nonce":"cGSj4BRb8rPXQwxIw7OtqvtSZZQ=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOAW4Y0s5pRhb0","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/5366","origin":"github"},"title":"FASTQ to FASTA tool: gzipped output has fasta datatype","message":"Just popped this out of https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/5333.\n\nThis is for the fastx_toolkit tool: https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/tree/main/tool_collections/fastx_toolkit/fastq_to_fasta\n\n**Issue:** The tool attempts to infer the FASTA output compression (none, gz or bz) from the input datatype. The tool does compress the data correctly, but always sets the output datatype as `fasta` resulting in a broken/weird dataset.\n\nI like the suggestion from @bernt-matthias :+1: \n\u003e My preference would be to have zipping/unzipping controlled by a select with the following options:\n\u003e\n\u003e - same as input (default)\n\u003e - zipped\n\u003e - unzipped\n\u003e\n\u003e So we have the best of both worlds. Unfortunately this brings a bit of \"heavy\" logic for determining the output format. Could be implemented with tool provided metadata (galaxy.json).\n\u003e \n\u003e Otherwise my (weak) preference would be \"same as input\"...\n\u003e \n\u003e What about fastqsanger.bz\n\u003e \n\u003e Is this a thing? :)\n\n... so will implement that.\n\nI'm working on a solution for inferring the output datatype that uses two outputs (one `fasta`, one `fasta.gz`) with a filter on each. Something like:\n\n```xml\n        \u003cdata name=\"output\" format=\"fasta\" metadata_source=\"input\"\u003e\n            \u003cfilter\u003e\n                not param_compressed_output\n                or input.is_of_type('fasta', 'fastqsanger', 'fastqsolexa', 'fastqillumina')\n            \u003c/filter\u003e\n        \u003c/data\u003e\n        \u003cdata name=\"output\" format=\"fasta.gz\" metadata_source=\"input\"\u003e\n            \u003cfilter\u003e param_compressed_output\n                or input.is_of_type(\n                    'fasta.gz',\n                    'fastqsanger.gz',\n                    'fastqsolexa.gz',\n                    'fastqillumina.gz',\n                    'fastqsanger.bz2',\n                    'fastqsolexa.bz2',\n                    'fastqillumina.bz2',\n                )\n            \u003c/filter\u003e\n        \u003c/data\u003e\n```\n\nLooks somewhat hacky to me, but it's the only way I could see to make the `format` attribute dynamic (unless there is some magic to be done with metadata as Matthias suggests). At least it's fairly readable.","files":null}]}